------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Filename conventions
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Filenames follow the pattern 

    <DOI_PREFIX>#<DOI_SUFFIX>(#<TAG>)*.<EXTENSION>
    
The first two parts connected by a forward slash constitute a DOI (see
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_object_identifier) that can be used to
find the online version of the source document using the URL
http://dx.doi.org/<DOI_PREFIX>/<DOI_SUFFIX>.

Filename tags denote:

    #full         = full article text
    #abs          = article abstract
    #sent         = selected sentences (one per line) extracted from xml source  
    #brat_XX      = annotated with Brat by annotator XX
    #scnlp_vX.Y.Z = annotated with Stanford CoreNLP, version X.Y.Z 


File extensions denote:

    .txt = plain text, UTF-8 character encoding
    .xml = XML markup for publication source or linguistic annotation
    .soa = stand-off annotation (labeled text spans)
    .ann = Brat stand-off annotation
    .bib = citation info in Bibtex format

So for example

    10.1371#journal.pone.0079890#full#sent#scnlp_v3.4.1.xml
    
is the Stanford CoreNLP (version 3.4.1) annotation for selected
sentences from the full text of the article with DOI
10.1371/journal.pone.0079890.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Directory structure
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    data/bib     = Bibtex files
    data/brat    = Brat text and annotation
    data.brat/XX = annotations by annotator XX
    data/scnlp   = Stanford CoreNLP annotation
    data/sent    = text from soa as one sentence per line
    data/soa     = stand-off annotation and corresponding text
    data/xml     = XML source

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Notes
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

- The brat dir can be directly copied to, or symlinked under, the
  DATA_DIR as defined in Brat's config.py file.

- The *.txt files in the brat directory are symlinks from *.txt files
  in the data/sent directory

- Abstracts from the pilot were obtained through copy & paste from the
  PDF file, so these have no XML source files.

- Conversion from xml to stand-off annotation was done using the
  nxml2txt script.

- Sentence splitting for the other abstracts and full texts was done
  with Stanford CoreNLP.

- Some abstracts lack any Brat annotation. This is not an error. It simply
  means no relevant events are present.

- The "methods" sections of full text articles has so far not been
  annotated, because these seem to contain hardly any general events.


